{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521850"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:37:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:37:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13762"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13762"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.26,0.32,0.37,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6382"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51154"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6382"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13762"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36426"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1710"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2053"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36144"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38975"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42921"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51154"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department of a rural hospital by paramedics after being found unresponsive while snowboarding at a nearby ski resort. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 6. His pulse rate is 40/min, blood pressure 80/40 mmHg, respiratory rate 8/min, SpO2 92% on high-flow oxygen, and core temperature 27\u00b0C. He is intubated for airway protection. Initial ECG shows sinus bradycardia which then progresses to ventricular fibrillation. CPR is commenced and three initial attempts at defibrillation are unsuccessful.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Defibrillation","Amiodarone 300 mg IV","Adrenaline 1 mg IV","Active external rewarming","Transfer to a tertiary hospital"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has severe hypothermia (core temperature \u0026lt;28\u00b0C) with cardiac arrest. In this setting, \u003Cstrong\u003Eactive external rewarming\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. The priority in severe hypothermia is to increase the core body temperature while continuing CPR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E can be given if appropriate up to three times in severe hypothermia but should then be withheld until the core temperature is above 30\u00b0C. Additionally, some guidelines recommend no defibrillation until the core temperature is above 30\u00b0C. The myocardium is very irritable in severe hypothermia, and defibrillation can precipitate refractory ventricular fibrillation (VF). Once the core temperature reaches 30\u00b0C, defibrillation can be attempted if still required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E and other anti-arrhythmic medications have limited effectiveness and can accumulate to toxic levels in severe hypothermia. Whilst this would normally be the appropriate time (after 3 shocks of a shockable rhythm) in the advanced life support algorithm, its use should be restricted until the core temperature is \u0026gt;30\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E and other advanced life support medications should typically be restricted until the core temperature is \u0026gt;30\u00b0C and have the interval between doses doubled until the core temperature is \u0026gt;35\u00b0C. In severe hypothermia, these medications are less effective and can accumulate to dangerous levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to a tertiary hospital\u003C/strong\u003E may be required for advanced rewarming techniques like cardiopulmonary bypass if the patient remains hemodynamically unstable despite initial rewarming measures. However, the immediate priority is to initiate active external rewarming while continuing CPR. Additionally, limited movement of patients is recommended due to the risk of triggering VF with movement due to the irritable myocardium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of severe hypothermia with cardiac arrest involves continuous CPR, active rewarming (using forced air rewarming blankets, warm IV fluids, and other available methods), and withholding \u0026gt;3 defibrillations and medications until appropriate core temperatures are reached. The goal is to rewarm the patient to above 30\u00b0C before attempting defibrillation, while providing continuous cardiopulmonary support.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Defibrillation should be withheld or limited to maximum 3 attempts in severe hypothermia until the core temperature is above 30\u00b0C, as it can precipitate refractory ventricular fibrillation.","Rewarming is the priority in managing severe hypothermia.","CPR should be continued during rewarming in hypothermic cardiac arrest."],"references":["Hypothermia. Life in the Fast Lane (LITFL) - Medical Blog [Internet]. 2019. Available at: https://litfl.com/hypothermia/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36426"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13762"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36426"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-21T18:21:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-21T18:24:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6382"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51154"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","posit